    "raw_ocr_text": "VII |\nII nr. 1 inneholder bestemmelsene om Kongressens og Presi- .\n\u00e5entens \"War Powers\", Bestemmelsene g\u00e5r bl.a. ut p\u00e5 at Kon-\ngressen kan erkl\u00e6re krigs opprette arm\u00e5 og fl\u00e5te, utfer\u00e5ige\nregler for disse samt at presidenten er \u00f8verstkommanderende.\nI tilslutning til den myndighet som er gitt Kongressen heter\ndet i art. I sec. 6 nr. 18 at den her anledning til:\n\n\"To make all Laws which shall be necessary and pro-\nper for cerrying into Execution the foregoing Powers, and\nall other Powers vested by this Constitution in the Go-\nvernment of the United States, or in any Department or\nOfficer thereof.\"\n\nVe\u00e5 utferdigelsen av disse lovene kan Konstitusjonen g\u00e5s for\nn\u00e6r. Hvorvidt man 4 en given situasjon ken sette seg ut ove\ndenne, kommer Corwin inn p\u00e5 , side 56-58:\n\n\"It ought to be remembered that even before the\nConstitution was adopted the American people had asserted\ntbeir right to wage war as & unit, and to act fin regard\nto all their foreign relations as a unit. Taking account\nof thet fact the Supreme Court in 1936, spesking by Justic\nSutherland, adopted the view, first advanced in 1792, tha\nthe National Government does not get its powers in these\nfields from the Constitution, but possesses them as an\ninherent attribute of national sovereignty, and that what\n\nE the above-mentloned and other relevant clauses of the\nConstitution do 18 simply to regulate in certain particu\u00bb-\nlars tbe exercise of these powers. In different phrase\n0logy, the \"war powers\" are comprised in one all=inclusiv\nWar Power, which may be defined as the power to take any\nand all measures to wage war successfully unless such\nmeasures are clearly forbidden by the Constitution, Thys\nsilence on the part of the Constitution in this field of\nnatlonal action, instead of being \u00e5 denial of the power\nto act, 18 an affirmance tlereof. .es\u00abserren\n\nNo doubt it is true, as former Chief Justice\nHughes once put it, when \"we are in war ..+WwO are not in\nrevolution.\" What M.r Hughes was thinking of, presumebly,\nwere the restraints which are imposed by the Bill of\nRights in behalf of private rights, and especially the\n\"due process\" clause of Amendment V: \"nor shall sny persog\nbe deprived of life, liberty, or property without due pro\n\ncess of law\" \u00bb that is, without what the Supreme Court finds\nto be justifying circumstances. But Total War is itself\na higbly justifying, not to say compulsive circumstance,\nin the presence of which judicial review is apt to be pro\nperly self-distrustful, and hence ineffective.\"\nForfatteren viser her til den vel\u00e5ige myndighet som \u00a3 U.S.A.\nunder siste krig var gitt til visse nyopprettede administra-\ntive kontorer, og som passerte uten hindringer fra domsto-\n",
